Load packages

library(tidyverse) 
library(datasauRus)

Exercise 1

1846 rows and 3 columns. The variables are: dataset, x, and y.

Exercise 2

Get the data we need and filter out anything that is not part of the dino dataset. We will then tell R how to display it (with a plot).

dino_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "dino")

ggplot(data = dino_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Finally calculate the the relation between x and y.

dino_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0645

Exercise 3

Filter out any data not part of the star set and place that data in star_data. Then we will tell R how to display the data.

star_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "star")

ggplot(data = star_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Calculate the r between x and y from the star_data.

star_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0630

Exercise 5

Plot all the datasets instead of just one.

ggplot(data = datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y, color = dataset)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~ dataset, ncol = 3) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Group all the datasets and then get the r between x and y for each dataset.

datasaurus_dozen %>%
  group_by(dataset) %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y)) %>%
  print(13)
## # A tibble: 13 x 2
##    dataset          r
